The runtime layer: container-d, run-see, and the alternatives.

We're back at the very center of the map. From module one: the daemon doesn't run containers itself. The docker daemon hands off to container-d, the runtime supervisor, which tracks lifecycle, and container-d drives run-see, the low-level o-c-i runtime that does the namespace, see-group, and exec dance, and becomes the container's process-I-D one. You almost never touch this layer, but knowing it's swappable explains a class of advanced setups.

Run-see is just one of several o-c-i runtimes, and they're interchangeable, because they share a standard interface. Crun is a C reimplementation of run-see that starts containers about ten times faster, and uses less memory; it's a low-risk drop-in, which you select by setting the default-runtime to crun. Kata-runtime runs each container inside a lightweight virtual machine, for real hardware isolation; it's heavier, but it fixes the, a container is not a security boundary, problem from module eight, for multi-tenant clusters. And g-visor, also called run-s-c, is a userspace kernel: it reimplements much of the Linux system-call surface in Go, intercepting the container's system calls before they reach the host kernel; that's strong isolation, at a modest performance cost. You register one in daemon dot j-son, and select it per container, with the runtime flag.

Now the bigger picture. Container-d is a standalone project, not Docker-only. Kubernetes talks to it directly, through the container runtime interface, skipping the docker daemon entirely. That's what the, Kubernetes deprecated Docker, headlines really meant; they dropped the docker-daemon shim, not your images. Your o-c-i images run identically on container-d, whether under Docker or under Kubernetes. Understanding this stack, daemon, to container-d, to runtime, to kernel, is what lets you reason about performance, isolation strength, and how Docker relates to the wider container ecosystem.
